  "why": "The ASDF framework assumes and enforces realistic, determinable inputs (naturalness) via cross-referencing that discards transformed texts not transcribable by at least one ASR service, and it performs local text mutations (tense/plurality/adjacent-deletion, homophone substitution) on failed texts (i.e., mutations relative to the previous failed input). However, ASDF does not enforce semantic equivalence relative to the original seed across iterations (it generates new example sentences for homophone transformations and appends transformed texts to the corpus), nor does it describe mechanisms to prevent cumulative semantic drift relative to the original seed. Thus it enforces naturalness and local semantic plausibility between successive mutations but does not account for cumulative distortion across iterations, matching the \"Medium\" definition.",
